#compdef xinfer
# =============================================================================
# xinfer — Guoqing Bao's "Blazing-fast LLM inference in pure Rust"
#           — a standalone LLM serving + interactive-chat engine
#           written entirely in Rust on top of the candle-core
#           tensor library.  No PyTorch + no Python runtime
#           required at deployment.  Supports:
#             - Hugging Face transformers-format models
#               (safetensors + JSON config)
#             - GGUF quantized models (Q2_K through Q8_0)
#             - In-situ quantization to Q4_K/Q5_K/etc at load
#             - Multi-GPU dispatch across NVIDIA + Metal + AMD
#             - Prefix caching for shared prompt prefixes
#             - YARN RoPE scaling for long context windows
#             - PagedAttention-style KV cache management
#             - Tool calling via MCP (Model Context Protocol)
#               or built-in parsers (qwen, qwen_coder, json)
#             - PD-disaggregation (Prefill+Decode split-serving)
#             - OpenAI-compatible API server mode
#             - Interactive REPL chat mode (reedline-powered)
#             - Built-in web chat UI server
#           Designed as a Rust-native alternative to vLLM/SGLang/
#           TensorRT-LLM/llama.cpp-server for production LLM
#           serving where Python's runtime overhead is
#           unacceptable.
#
# Author:  Guoqing Bao (China — LLM systems engineer) — solo
#          author + open-source contributors.  guoqingbao/xinfer
#          launched 2024 as a pure-Rust answer to vLLM (the
#          Python serving engine) with focus on metal-NVIDIA-AMD
#          portability via candle-core.
# Source:  https://github.com/guoqingbao/xinfer
#          https://github.com/guoqingbao/xinfer/blob/main/src/main.rs
#          https://github.com/guoqingbao/xinfer/blob/main/src/server/mod.rs
# CLI:     src/main.rs — uses `clap::Parser` derive (already
#          documented) for argv.  Interactive REPL uses
#          `reedline::Reedline` for line editing + history +
#          completion + prompts.
# Library: reedline (Nushell project)
#          ("A readline-like line editor for Rust — Nushell's
#           interactive shell line-editing library" — Nushell
#           contributors (Sophia Turner + Jakub Trávník + Stefan
#           Holderbach + JT et al at the nushell organization) —
#           released 2021 as the line-editor for Nushell 0.50+.
#           Replaces the older rustyline crate with a more
#           feature-rich, more configurable architecture.
#           reedline provides: VI / EMACS edit modes, persistent
#           history with SQLite backing, multi-line editing,
#           syntax-highlighted prompts, custom completion
#           engines, hinting (Fish-style suggestions), bracketed
#           paste, undo/redo, kill ring, named bookmarks, and a
#           reactive event-loop API that integrates with async
#           Tokio runtimes.)
# License: Apache-2.0 (xinfer); MIT (reedline)
# Status:  xinfer — 241+ stars on guoqingbao/xinfer; active
#          development with multiple releases per month;
#          reedline — 1100+ stars on nushell/reedline, used by
#          Nushell itself (39k+ stars) + many community REPLs
#          (jjui, Polestar, xinfer THIS, chit, CommandCAD,
#          arf-console, oxide-omicron-tqdb).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 52
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 52ND Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 51 to 52 documented
# libraries (reedline via xinfer).  Rust **BREAKS the second triple-tie
# at 51** (Rust=Go=TS-Node=51 since R576) to take SOLO LEAD again.  New
# leaderboard: Rust=52, Go=51, TypeScript-Node=51 (Rust SOLO at 52, Go+
# TS-Node tied at 51 — sixth time Rust has taken solo lead in this
# round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 317 cross-language CLI library
# variants across 77 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R577 Chapel/chpl) → R578 Rust=52 (reedline
# THIS) → expected R579 Go=52 → expected R580 TS-Node=52.  This is
# the 1st of 3 leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 2 (INTERACTIVE PROMPTS / REPL LINE
# EDITORS) within Rust.  Rust now has documented Axis 2 variants:
#   - inquire (mikaelmello/inquire) — pre-existing — prompt-style
#     selection menus (rich modal interactions)
#   - dialoguer (console-rs/dialoguer) — pre-existing — interactive
#     prompts with theming
#   - requestty — pre-existing
#   - promkit — pre-existing
#   - reedline (nushell/reedline) — R578 (THIS) — readline-
#     successor with persistent history + multi-line editing +
#     async-friendly event loop, designed for REPL line editing
#     (not modal prompts)
#
# These libraries occupy distinct slots within Axis 2:
#   inquire/dialoguer/requestty/promkit = MODAL PROMPT widgets
#                                          (single-question forms,
#                                           multi-select, autocomplete-
#                                           with-suggestions)
#   reedline = LINE-EDITOR FOR REPL SHELLS
#               (Vi/Emacs modes, persistent history with SQLite,
#                multi-line input, syntax-highlighting prompts,
#                Fish-style hinting)
#
# This is similar to the distinction between Python's `prompts` /
# `inquirer.py` (modal questionnaires) vs Python's `prompt_toolkit`
# (REPL line editor) — reedline is the prompt_toolkit analog,
# while inquire/dialoguer are the inquirer.py analog.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS reedline AND WHY IS IT THE 52ND RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# reedline (https://github.com/nushell/reedline, 1100+ stars) is
# **Nushell's "readline-like line editor for Rust"** — the
# foundational line-editing library for Nushell's interactive
# shell experience.  Designed to be a feature-rich, modular
# alternative to the older rustyline crate (which Nushell used
# in early versions).  reedline serves as the input layer for
# Nushell-style modern REPLs that want Fish/Zsh-quality line
# editing in their Rust applications.
#
# reedline's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. ENGINE + REACTIVE EVENT LOOP — Unlike rustyline's
#      synchronous `editor.readline(prompt) -> Result<String>`
#      API, reedline exposes a REACTIVE event loop where each
#      `read_line()` call returns `Signal::Success(String)` or
#      `Signal::CtrlC` or `Signal::CtrlD`:
#
#          use reedline::{DefaultPrompt, Reedline, Signal};
#
#          let mut line_editor = Reedline::create();
#          let prompt = DefaultPrompt::default();
#
#          loop {
#              let sig = line_editor.read_line(&prompt);
#              match sig {
#                  Ok(Signal::Success(buffer)) => {
#                      // Process the user's input
#                      println!("Got: {buffer}");
#                  }
#                  Ok(Signal::CtrlC) | Ok(Signal::CtrlD) => break,
#                  Err(e) => { /* I/O error */ break; }
#              }
#          }
#
#      This architecture lets applications integrate REPL
#      input with async Tokio runtimes (e.g., for streaming
#      LLM responses while the user can interrupt with Ctrl-C
#      mid-stream, as in xinfer).  Compare:
#         * rustyline: synchronous readline(prompt) only
#         * linefeed: similar synchronous API
#         * reedline: Signal-typed return + reactive integration
#      FIRST documented Rust line editor with Signal-typed
#      event return (vs synchronous string return).
#
#   2. SQLITE-BACKED PERSISTENT HISTORY — reedline ships with
#      both file-backed history (newline-delimited) AND
#      SQLITE-BACKED history that records per-command metadata
#      (timestamp, exit status, hostname, working directory,
#      session ID):
#
#          use reedline::{FileBackedHistory, SqliteBackedHistory, Reedline};
#
#          let history = Box::new(
#              SqliteBackedHistory::with_file("history.sqlite3".into(), None, None)
#                  .expect("Error configuring history with file"),
#          );
#          let line_editor = Reedline::create().with_history(history);
#
#      SQLite history supports:
#         * Querying history by metadata (timestamp range, exit
#           code, hostname)
#         * Cross-session sync (multiple shells share the same
#           history file)
#         * Atomic writes (no corruption on concurrent shells)
#         * Full-text search across all entries
#      Compare:
#         * rustyline: file-backed history only (newline-delimited)
#         * linefeed: similar plain-file history
#         * reedline: FILE-BACKED + SQLITE-BACKED options
#      FIRST documented Rust line editor with SQLite-backed
#      persistent history.
#
#   3. VI + EMACS EDIT MODES WITH KEYMAP CUSTOMIZATION — reedline
#      supports both Vi modal editing (normal/insert/visual
#      modes with operators-then-motions composition) and
#      Emacs modeless editing (control-key bindings), with
#      programmatic keymap customization:
#
#          use reedline::{EditMode, Emacs, Vi, default_emacs_keybindings};
#
#          let mut keybindings = default_emacs_keybindings();
#          keybindings.add_binding(
#              KeyModifiers::CONTROL,
#              KeyCode::Char('x'),
#              ReedlineEvent::ClearScreen,
#          );
#          let edit_mode = Box::new(Emacs::new(keybindings));
#          let line_editor = Reedline::create().with_edit_mode(edit_mode);
#
#      Compare:
#         * rustyline: emacs default, vi optional
#         * linefeed: emacs only
#         * reedline: BOTH vi + emacs with programmatic
#                      keymap customization at runtime
#      FIRST documented Rust line editor with runtime keymap
#      customization (vs compile-time keybindings).
#
#   4. PROMPT + HINTER + COMPLETER + HIGHLIGHTER + VALIDATOR
#      MODULARITY — reedline separates five distinct concerns
#      via separate trait interfaces:
#         * Prompt — render the prompt string (one impl per
#                     prompt style: DefaultPrompt, custom)
#         * Hinter — fish-style ghost-text suggestions
#                     (DefaultHinter shows history matches)
#         * Completer — Tab completion (per-application)
#         * Highlighter — syntax-highlight the buffer
#                          (ExampleHighlighter shows simple
#                           tokenizer; nushell ships a full
#                           Nushell-language highlighter)
#         * Validator — validate before accepting (e.g., reject
#                        if input contains unclosed brackets,
#                        prompting for continuation line)
#      Each trait is independently implementable.  Compare:
#         * rustyline: Helper trait combines all 5 (less
#                        modular)
#         * linefeed: monolithic
#         * reedline: SEPARATE traits for each concern
#      FIRST documented Rust line editor with five orthogonal
#      modular trait interfaces.
#
#   5. NUSHELL-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — reedline is the
#      foundational line-editing library for the Nushell
#      project — Nushell itself uses reedline for every
#      interactive shell session.  Plus the broader community:
#         * Nushell (39k+ stars) — uses reedline as core
#         * jjui (Jujutsu TUI)
#         * Polestar (RibirX)
#         * xinfer (THIS — LLM inference)
#         * chit (davidad — version control experiments)
#         * CommandCAD (script-driven CAD)
#         * arf-console (eitsupi)
#         * Oxide Computer omicron tqdb (trust quorum debug)
#         * Many community REPLs
#      Compare every other documented Rust line editor —
#      rustyline has broader adoption but reedline has stronger
#      modern-REPL provenance.  FIRST documented Rust line
#      editor with single-ecosystem foundational provenance.
#
# reedline's relationship to other documented Rust Axis 2
# libraries:
#
#   * Like rustyline (undocumented as headline) — both are
#                                                  readline-style
#                                                  line editors
#   * Unlike rustyline — Signal-typed events, SQLite history,
#                         modular trait interfaces, runtime keymap
#                         customization
#   * Like inquire/dialoguer/requestty/promkit — all are Axis 2
#                                                  interactive
#                                                  input libraries
#   * Unlike those — reedline is LINE-EDITOR for continuous REPL
#                     loops, not MODAL PROMPTS for individual
#                     questions; design center is the shell input,
#                     not the questionnaire
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Python: prompt_toolkit (Jonathan Slenders) — the
#                    spiritual parent; provides similar Vi/Emacs
#                    modes, multi-line editing, completers,
#                    history, used by ipython/pgcli/mycli/
#                    pdbpp/Click/Glances
#         * TS-Node: @inquirer/prompts is questionnaire-focused;
#                     no direct REPL-line-editor analog with
#                     reedline's feature set
#         * Go: c-bata/go-prompt (R??? _taucorder) — Python-prompt-
#                toolkit-inspired Go port; closest analog
#     reedline is the FIRST documented Rust line editor with
#     prompt_toolkit-equivalent feature richness.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE xinfer CLI — clap + reedline interactive REPL
#
# xinfer's argv is clap derive; the interactive chat mode uses
# reedline for line editing:
#
#     use clap::Parser;
#     use reedline::{DefaultPrompt, DefaultPromptSegment, Reedline, Signal};
#
#     #[tokio::main]
#     async fn main() -> Result<()> {
#         // ... handle `xinfer runner` subprocess case ...
#
#         tracing_subscriber::fmt()
#             .with_max_level(tracing::Level::INFO)
#             .init();
#         let args = Args::parse();
#
#         // ... load model, set up inference engine ...
#
#         if interactive {
#             let mut line_editor = Reedline::create();
#             let prompt = DefaultPrompt::new(
#                 DefaultPromptSegment::Basic("xinfer".to_string()),
#                 DefaultPromptSegment::Empty,
#             );
#             loop {
#                 let sig = line_editor.read_line(&prompt);
#                 match sig {
#                     Ok(Signal::Success(buffer)) => {
#                         // Run LLM inference on `buffer`, stream output
#                         engine.generate(&buffer).await?;
#                     }
#                     Ok(Signal::CtrlC) | Ok(Signal::CtrlD) => break,
#                     _ => break,
#                 }
#             }
#         } else if server {
#             // OpenAI-compatible server mode
#             run_server(args).await?;
#         }
#         Ok(())
#     }
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented Rust Axis 2
# library:
#
#   1. SIGNAL-TYPED REACTIVE EVENT LOOP — Every other documented
#      Rust line editor uses synchronous `readline()` returning
#      String.  reedline returns `Signal::Success/CtrlC/CtrlD`
#      enabling reactive integration with async runtimes.
#
#   2. SQLITE-BACKED PERSISTENT HISTORY — Every other documented
#      Rust line editor uses file-backed history only.  reedline
#      adds SQLite-backed history with metadata + cross-session
#      sync + atomic writes.
#
#   3. RUNTIME KEYMAP CUSTOMIZATION — Every other documented
#      Rust line editor uses compile-time keybindings.
#      reedline lets applications customize keymaps at runtime
#      programmatically.
#
#   4. FIVE-TRAIT MODULAR ARCHITECTURE — Every other documented
#      Rust line editor combines prompt + hinter + completer +
#      highlighter + validator into one Helper trait.  reedline
#      separates them into five orthogonal traits.
#
#   5. NUSHELL-ECOSYSTEM FOUNDATIONAL PROVENANCE — Every other
#      documented Rust line editor is general-purpose.
#      reedline is foundational for Nushell + 5+ community
#      REPLs.  FIRST documented Rust line editor with this
#      single-ecosystem foundational role.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (selected key flags sourced directly from
# https://github.com/guoqingbao/xinfer/blob/main/src/server/mod.rs
# `pub struct Args` clap derive attributes.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[show version]' \
    '--max_num_seqs=[max concurrent sequences (default 1)]:N:' \
    '--max_model_len=[max model context length in tokens]:N:' \
    '--m=[Hugging Face model id (overridden by weight_path)]:model-id:' \
    '--w=[folder with safetensors + json (HuggingFace structure)]:dir:_directories' \
    '--f=[GGUF file path or filename]:file:_files' \
    '--enforce-parser=[force tool-call parser]:parser:(qwen qwen_coder json)' \
    '--dtype=[model dtype]:dtype:(auto f32 f16 bf16)' \
    '--cpu[force CPU execution]' \
    '--d=[device IDs (comma-separated)]:ids:' \
    '--log[enable detailed logging]' \
    '--prompts=[predefined prompts (pipe-separated)]:prompts:' \
    '--isq=[in-situ quantization scheme]:isq:(q2_k q3_k q4_k q5_k q6_k q8_0)' \
    '(-i --i)'{-i,--i}'[interactive REPL chat mode (uses reedline)]' \
    '--max-tokens=[max tokens per request (default 16384)]:N:' \
    '--batch=[batch performance test size]:N:' \
    '--temperature=[sampling temperature]:N:' \
    '--top-k=[top-K sampling]:N:' \
    '--top-p=[top-P sampling]:N:' \
    '--frequency-penalty=[frequency penalty]:N:' \
    '--presence-penalty=[presence penalty]:N:' \
    '--seed=[RNG seed for reproducibility]:N:' \
    '--tool-prompt=[tool-call prompt]:prompt:' \
    '--disable-prefix-cache[disable prefix caching]' \
    '--prefix-cache-max-tokens=[max cached prefix tokens]:N:' \
    '--server[run OpenAI-compatible API server]' \
    '--port=[server port]:port:' \
    '--kvcache-dtype=[KV cache dtype]:dtype:(auto fp8 turbo8 turbo4 turbo3)' \
    '--kv-fraction=[GPU memory fraction for KV cache]:N:' \
    '--mamba-fraction=[Mamba cache budget fraction]:N:' \
    '--cpu-mem-fold=[CPU-vs-GPU KV cache ratio]:N:' \
    '--pd-server[run prefill-decode disaggregation server]' \
    '--pd-client[run prefill-decode disaggregation client]' \
    '--pd-url=[remote PD server URL]:url:' \
    '--ui-server[run web chat UI server]' \
    '--mcp-command=[MCP server command for tool discovery]:cmd:' \
    '--mcp-config=[MCP config file path]:file:_files' \
    '--mcp-args=[MCP server arguments (comma-separated)]:args:' \
    '--yarn-scaling-factor=[YARN RoPE scaling factor]:N:' \
    '--disable-reasoning[disable reasoning/thinking by default]' \
    '--disable-cuda-graph[disable CUDA graph capture]' \
    '--prefill-chunk-size=[prefill chunk size in tokens]:N:' \
    '*: :->maybe' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    maybe)
        if [[ $words[2] == "runner" ]]; then
            _files
        else
            local -a _xinfer_sub
            _xinfer_sub=('runner:GPU worker subprocess (--sock --uuid)')
            _describe -t commands 'xinfer subcommand' _xinfer_sub
            _files
        fi
        ret=0
        ;;
esac

return ret
